         <div>
            <head>5.6.1884 Donnerstag</head>
            <p>
               <placeName type="write" key="49396">Wernigerode</placeName> June 5. 1884</p>
            <p>Started from <placeName key="80103">Harzburg</placeName>
               <note type="reg">
                  <placeName key="80103">Bad Harzburg</placeName>
               </note> this morning at 9.15. We rode
               through the wood down to the Radanthal and waterfall which was not very pretty as it
               was being repaired and very little water was coming down. We then rode past some
               large quarries and over the Radan and on through the wood over the mountain to the
               Molkenhaus and from there went to the Muxklippe, from which there is a very fine view
               on to the Brocken. We then walked down a very steep hill leading our horses as it was
               too steep to ride. As off we passed the Ecker my horses eyes had to be tied up as it
               would not have gone over had that not been done. On the other side we had go through
               the preserves of <persName key="17501">the count of Stolberg-Wernigerode</persName>
               till we got to <placeName key="49402">Scharfenstein</placeName> after which the
               little Brocken begins; and no wonder they thought it haunted. It is so covered with
               rocks and large stones that the horses could hardly get up it. The big Brocken which
               we got on after is not so bad. When we got to the top we went up the tower from which
               though the weather was not good we had a fine view. We then had a very good dinner in
               the <orgName key="81637">Brockenhotel</orgName> and after it rode down in 2 hours to
                  <placeName key="49402">Ilseburg</placeName> by the Ilse falls which are very
               pretty. At <placeName key="49402">Ilseburg</placeName> we went to the <orgName key="66853">Hotel zu den roten forellen</orgName> and had beer and coffee there
               and from there went by the train to <placeName key="49396">Wernigerode</placeName>
               where we are living in <placeName key="66854">the weisse Hirsch</placeName>. </p>
         </div>
